  abstract = {In the semantics of human collective nouns there are two mechanisms at work, leading to distinct types of collectivity. The collectivity of `crowds' is based on the contiguity of its elements, while the contiguity of `clubs' is based on membership in a social institution. This proposal strengthens and unifies earlier proposals about the nature and typology of collective nouns; it accounts for a range of new and old observations about the variety of collective nouns and it connects to recent insights in the study of collective reference more generally.},
